##317 It's impossible to predict when the sun will shine

The neighbor on the left had been weeding in the backyard in the morning and figured out that she was taking a break from home to call workers to lay bricks for the backyard -- as if she had just started work from home, and was eager to give her house a new day. In the afternoon, there was the sound of "Hiss" and "tuk-tuk" grinding bricks and hammering. Fortunately, all kinds of sounds were not high. The neighbor on the right had been playing music all day, and for a while it even sounded like yue-ju, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or yue-ji, or.

Video with my mother in the morning, my mother is to shake sound reciting ancient poetry. She recited the Song "Hills and Rivers Remain, city spring trees deep" , she recited the "letter home to all gold" , I asked her to see my day more like she said, no! Then she recited another Du Fu Song, "the river bird is more white than white, the mountain blue and white is burning. This spring, see again, when the year is back. " When my mother recited a word, stumbled, of course, she does not remember, but my heart also shivers.

The Sun is too bright. Find oneself also infected with the British mood, there is sunshine when I feel that the Sun should go to stand, lie down, sit. It doesn't rain all the time in the south of England, there's always a moment when the sun shines on most days, but one can't predict when that moment will be, except that it's like a rainstorm, a hailstorm, or a gale, it's constant, but it's brief. So, to complain about bad weather is to not have found a way to cope with it -- my landlord lived in Paris for almost 30 years, and she found the weather more difficult than in London, as if it were cloudy, but London is different, AH, "If I wake up and it's clear outside, I think, oh no, it's going to rain later, and if it's cloudy in the morning, it might clear up for a while at noon! " I said if you put this awareness of British weather into an understanding of China's policy instability, it just went through.

After all, I am home today. This morning I sent a home disinfection guide to my English teachers and friends. C, who works in the art department of Jnby in Hangzhou, gave it to me. They prepared this three-page message for the foreign staff in the department, it's about what to wear when you leave the house, how to disinfect the house. After I sent it, some of my friends emailed me back -- as if the British were finally starting to get nervous, and some artists said they had done it all in accordance with the home health and sanitation manual. And most of my friends who work at the gallery have started or are about to start working from home, as suggested by the British government, the word is still should, a strong suggestion, in a way, it is still the case that institutions, companies, and universities are taking more and different measures, sooner or later, than the government requires. The Tate says it will be closed until May 1st; friends who work in the city will have to work from home for two weeks, but some bosses can't tell the difference between work from home and work 724; gyms and cafes are mostly open, but keep it far enough apart.

Of course, there is a situation where we have different opinions about the system at hand, for example, my mailbox sometimes gets a new email every few minutes, not an event cancellation email, not a notice from the school, instead, RCA students were writing letters demanding that the school close the campus and extend the school year. What I've been going through is that everyone has to think for themselves: from the teachers and students who went on strike at RCA, to the petitions of citizens against government policies, to the open debate on the epidemic on BBC 4, there are people who try to negotiate, to negotiate, to believe that words and actions matter. The British government believes that gradual isolation will help to slow the epidemic, and that's a position, a very important position, and the rest is for each individual to judge, to speak out, to organize themselves, and if they object, to interact with the system.

In the afternoon, I spent three hours on Zoom, and my philosophy class turned into a discussion with more than 20 people. The philosophy teacher asked, at this moment, how can we mobilize ourselves to do active construction, activate the agency? The artists'thinking, for the most part, was based more on humanity than on calculations of how to run society, and more on taking care of the elderly around them and the people on the streets so that they didn't have to die. But I was also surprised that even though the outbreak came from China, and even though most of the artists were reflecting on their central Western perspective, most students in Europe and the United States had not heard of Li Wenliang and Ms. I've been reading the Guardian since the outbreak, first from the left wing foreign media about China, and now about the local epidemic, but perhaps most of my classmates still have the UK as their main page, instead of going into the APP like I did and saying, "World. ".

A classmate said she was going to a seminar next month in Manchester called Laughter in the Crisis. Laughter, like so many other conferences, was cancelled. We are in the midst of a crisis, and we have to figure out for ourselves when to stop trying to force people to be optimistic and when to laugh at ourselves so that we can save ourselves, what is a good sense of humor? I have always felt that telling a joke is the most difficult part of mastering a foreign language, because to get the punch line right, one has to understand the other person's knowledge and mood. I've given up hope that I can go from dry humour to playful English humor, and the strategy is to dry humour until I feel as if I'm in a state of No! I am kidding! * ! Chinese humor is even more self-explanatory -- I like it when doctors and nurses in Wuhan painted Louis Vuitton and Gucci logos on transparent medical bags and said, "this year doesn't count, next year it will be 2020. " It's genius.

Of all the people who replied to my emails, there was a lovely old poet with a Dandy Dandy like Oscar Wilde. His name was Jeremy, and every time I saw him, I was overwhelmed by his high-spirited and somewhat charming expression, but I read his letters several times:

"Dear chloe... I now touch buttons and ATM buttons through a tissue, try to stay in the leafy Hampstead, eat zinc and the most immune-boosting propolis..

I miss you very much, and I hope that when the virus subsides, we can have tea together as soon as possible.

I hope you continue to create, as I do. I wish I could send you a big bouquet of spring flowers.

Signed, "Jeremy and the Purple Hyacinth, " as if I were flower's grandfather.
